SIMPLE: phenol
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Phenol
<hw>Phe"nol</hw> <pr>(f⟦emac⟧"n⟦omac⟧l; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[Gr. <grk>fai`nein</grk> to show + <ets>-ol</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>ph⟦eacute⟧nol</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
white or pinkish crystalline substance, <chform>C6H5OH</chform>,
produced by the destructive distillation of many organic bodies, as
wood, coal, etc., and obtained from the heavy oil from coal
tar.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ It has a peculiar odor, somewhat resembling creosote,
which is a complex mixture of phenol derivatives. It is of the type of
alcohols, and is called also <altname>phenyl alcohol</altname>, but has
acid properties, and hence is popularly called <altname>carbolic
acid</altname>, and was formerly called <altname>phenic acid</altname>.
It is a powerful caustic poison, and in dilute solution has been used as
an antiseptic.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any one of the series of hydroxyl derivatives of
which phenol proper is the type.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Glacial phenol</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>pure
crystallized phenol or carbolic acid.</cd> -- <col><b>Phenol
acid</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>any one of a series of compounds
which are at once a derivative of phenol and an organic acid; thus,
<stype>salicylic acid</stype> is a <ex>phenol acid</ex>.</cd> --
<col><b>Phenol alcohol</b></col> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>any one of
series of derivatives of phenol and carbinol which have the properties
of both combined; thus, <stype>saligenin</stype> is a <ex>phenol
alcohol</ex>.</cd> -- <col><b>Phenol aldehyde</b></col>
<fld>(Chem.)</fld>, <cd>any one of a series of compounds having both
phenol and aldehyde properties.</cd> -- <col><b>Phenol
phthalein</b></col>. <cd>See <er>phenolphthalein</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Phenolate</ent>⟦br⟧
